\(R^2\) represents the proportion of variance in rate explained by the predictors.

The full model explains approximately 67.7% of the variance in rate, while Model 1 explains 63.3% and Model 2 explains 46.4%.

Adding slim to trks and acpt increases \(R^2\) from 0.633 to 0.677. This is indicates that slim adds substantial explainability to the model. It captures important variation in rate not explained by the other two predictors.

Model 2 uses only slim and has the lowest \(R^2\) (0.464). This suggests that while slim is useful, it cannot explain as the variance alone as the combination of predictors in the other models can.

  1. For littletree manually calculate the decrease in Gini impurity after the first split R Method:
# (b) Gini decrease for littletree first split in R

# Gini helper
gini <- function(counts) {
  p <- counts / sum(counts)
  1 - sum(p^2)
}

# 1. Gini at the root (df_train, before split)
root_counts <- df_train |>
  count(Status) |>
  pull(n)

gini_parent <- gini(root_counts)

# 2. Gini in left and right child nodes after split on Bilirubin >= 2.25
left_node <- df_train |> filter(Bilirubin >= 2.25)
right_node <- df_train |> filter(Bilirubin < 2.25)

left_counts <- left_node |> count(Status) |> pull(n)
right_counts <- right_node |> count(Status) |> pull(n)

gini_left <- gini(left_counts)
gini_right <- gini(right_counts)

n_left <- nrow(left_node)
n_right <- nrow(right_node)
n_total <- n_left + n_right

# 3. Weighted Gini after the split
gini_after <- (n_left / n_total) * gini_left +
  (n_right / n_total) * gini_right

# 4. Decrease in Gini impurity
gini_decrease <- gini_parent - gini_after

c(
  gini_parent = gini_parent,
  gini_left = gini_left,
  gini_right = gini_right,
  gini_after = gini_after,
  gini_decrease = gini_decrease
)
  gini_parent     gini_left    gini_right    gini_after gini_decrease 
   0.45517946    0.45704518    0.31108493    0.36177771    0.09340175

Answer: about 0.0934

misclass_counts <- function(cm) {
  wrong_died     <- cm["survived", "died"]   # predicted died, actually survived
  wrong_survived <- cm["died", "survived"]   # predicted survived, actually died
  c(wrong_died = wrong_died,
    wrong_survived = wrong_survived)
}

misclass_counts(cm_train_big)

            30             30

    wrong_died wrong_survived 
            41             42 
misclass_counts(cm_test_big)
    wrong_died wrong_survived 
             8             22 
misclass_counts(cm_test_lit)
    wrong_died wrong_survived

Training data

bigtree accuracy: 0.82

Misclassifications: 30 wrongly predicted died (actually survived), 30 wrongly predicted survived (actually died).

littletree accuracy: 0.75

Misclassifications: 41 wrongly predicted died, 42 wrongly predicted survived.

So on the training set, bigtree is more accurate and makes fewer errors of both types, with errors roughly balanced in each model.

Test data

bigtree accuracy: 0.64

Misclassifications: 8 wrongly predicted died, 22 wrongly predicted survived.

littletree accuracy: 0.70

Misclassifications: 7 wrongly predicted died, 18 wrongly predicted survived.

On the test set, littletree actually performs better, it has higher accuracy and fewer of both kinds of misclassification errors, suggesting bigtree is overfitting the training data.

  1. Use the pdp with ggplot2 to create faceted graphs showing the partial dependence plots for the numeric variables in bigtree and forest. For each, the facets should be in decreasing order of standard deviation for yhat.

Note: Use the parameter prob = TRUE with partial() so the predictions will be probabilities.

library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(forcats)
library(ggplot2)
library(pdp)

## Helper: one-variable PDP in long format --------------------------
get_pdp_long <- function(model, train_dat, var) {
  pd <- partial(
    object  = model,
    pred.var = var,
    train   = train_dat,
    prob    = TRUE,          # probability scale
    which.class = "died",    # P(Status = "died")
    plot    = FALSE,
    grid.resolution = 20
  )
  
  tibble(
    variable = var,
    value    = pd[[var]],
    yhat     = pd$yhat       # <- this is the correct column name
  )
}

## ---------- bigtree PDPs (numeric predictors only) ----------------

num_vars_big <- df_train |>
  select(-Status) |>
  select(where(is.numeric)) |>
  names()

pdp_big_long <- map_dfr(
  num_vars_big,
  get_pdp_long,
  model = bigtree,
  train_dat = df_train
)

# order facets by decreasing sd(yhat)
sd_big <- pdp_big_long |>
  group_by(variable) |>
  summarise(sd_yhat = sd(yhat), .groups = "drop")

pdp_big_long <- pdp_big_long |>
  left_join(sd_big, by = "variable") |>
  mutate(variable = fct_reorder(variable, sd_yhat, .desc = TRUE))

ggplot(pdp_big_long, aes(x = value, y = yhat)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(
    x = "Predictor value",
    y = "P(Status = 'died')",
    title = "Partial dependence (numeric predictors) â bigtree"
  )

  1. Describe the similarities and differences in pdp plots within each and across the models.

In bigtree, the PDPs are step-like and only a few variables (like Prothrombin, Alk_Phos, Bilirubin, Albumin) actually move the predicted death probability, while the rest are basically flat. In the random forest, almost every numeric variable shows a smoother change in risk as the predictor changes. Across the two, both agree that higher Bilirubin/Prothrombin/Alk_Phos and lower Albumin mean higher risk of death, but the forest spreads the signal over more variables and in a less jumpy way.
